06060nam a22008535i 9783110599176DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20182019gw     fo  d z      ger d  a97831105991767 a10.1515/97831105991762doi  a(DE-B1597)494730  a(OCoLC)1083623632  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 ager  agwcDE 7aREL041000;BISACREL041000 2bisacsh04aDie Koranhermeneutik von Günter Lüling /chrsg. von Georges Tamer. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2018] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (VI, 223 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJudaism, Christianity, and Islam – Tension, Transmission, Transformation ,x2196-405X ;v900tFrontmatter -- tInhalt -- tGünter Lüling: Leben, Werk und Fall -- tGünter Lüling (1928–2014) als Lehrer -- tMartin Werner und Albert Schweitzer und ihre Bedeutung für die Arbeiten von Günter Lüling -- tLate Antique Christology in Qurʾānic Perspective -- tEine urchristliche Engelchristologie im Koran? -- tSanctuary and Text: How Far can the Qurʾān Throw Light on the History of the Muslim Sanctuary? -- tHermeneutische Dimensionen der Intertextualität und Interreligiöse Kontexte des Korans -- tDīn, Islām, und Muslim im Koran -- tQurʾānic Studies between Revisionism and Reinvention -- tQ 96 Sūrat al-ʿAlaq Between Philology and Polemics: A (Very) Critical Assessment of Günter Lüling’s Ur-Qurʾān -- tChances and problems with the morpho-syntactic analysis of the Qurʾān, based on a colometric representation -- tBibliographie -- tPersonenregister -- tSachregister0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDer koranhermeneutische Ansatz des Islamwissenschaftlers Günter Lüling (1928-2014) wurde jahrzehntelang von Fachvertretern totgeschwiegen, was Nahrung für Verschwörungstheorien lieferte. Seine Theorie, dass der Koran seinen Ursprung im alten Christentum habe, widersprach der traditionellen Wissenschaft seiner Zeit. Der Band enthält Forschungsbeiträge, in denen Lülings Werk erstmals kritisch gewürdigt wird.  aThe present volume offers the first scholarly discussion of Günter Lüling’s (1928-2014) work. Lüling’s views, long passages of the Qur’ān are originally mere reworking of pre-Islamic Christian hymns have not received the scholarly attention they deserve, since they were published at the beginning of the 70s of the previous century. Lüling attempted to reconstruct an “Ur-Qur’ān” in order to show that Islam emerged in a Christian context in Mecca. He also believed that Muhammad converted from Trinitarian Christianity to paganism and that the Kaaba was a church. Lüling’s hermeneutical approach to the Qur’ān and other Arabic sources on early Islam is, for the first time, the subject of the studies included in the present book. In addition, the volume offers interesting insights in the law case which accompanied the publication of Lüling’s work.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aGünter Lüling. 4aIslamwissenschaften. 4aKoranhermeneutik.  aGünter Lüling.  aIslamic studies.  aKoran hermeneutics.1 aBobzin, Hartmut, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonner, Fred M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdzard, Lutz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffith, Sidney H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawting, Gerald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorn, Cornelia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHundhammer, Marianus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStosch, Klaus von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTamer, Georges, econtributo